}
comparison_row: "" {
  direction: right
  style.stroke: transparent
  style.fill: transparent
  linear_problem: {
    label: "Linear Bucketing Problem"
    width: 320
    prob_desc: |md
      **Fixed 1μs buckets to cover 0-1s:**
      - Requires **1,000,000 buckets**
      - Most buckets are empty
      - Memory: ~8 MB per histogram
      - Cache-inefficient
    |
    style.fill: "#FFEBEE"
    style.stroke: "#C62828"
  }
  log2_solution: {
    label: "Log2 Bucketing Solution"
    width: 320
    sol_desc: |md
      **64 log2 buckets covers 0-18hrs:**
      - Only **64 buckets** needed
      - Every bucket gets samples
      - Memory: ~512 bytes per histogram
      - Cache-friendly
    |
    style.fill: "#E8F5E9"
    style.stroke: "#2E7D32"
  }
}
memory_layout: {
  label: "Memory Layout: Per-Syscall Histogram"
  shape: sql_table
  width: 500
  m0: "Bucket 0  | u64 | 0-1μs count"
  m1: "Bucket 1  | u64 | 1-2μs count"
  m2: "Bucket 2  | u64 | 2-4μs count"
  m3: "...       | u64 | ..."
  m62: "Bucket 62 | u64 | 2^62-2^63 μs"
  m63: "Bucket 63 | u64 | 2^63+ μs"
  total: "Total: 64 × 8 = 512 bytes (1 cache line = 64 bytes, ~8 lines)"
  style.fill: "#E3F2FD"
}
insight_box: {
  label: "Key Insight: Power-Law Distribution"
  width: 650
  insight_text: |md
    **Why log2 histograms work for syscalls:**
    1. **Typical distribution**: 90% of syscalls complete in <10μs (cached), 9% in 10μs-1ms (disk), 1% >1ms (network)
    2. **Linear buckets waste space**: 99% of samples would crowd into first 1000 buckets, leaving 999,000 empty
    3. **Log2 matches reality**: Bucket widths grow with typical latency variance—more resolution where samples cluster
    4. **Percentile calculation**: Cumulative sum from bucket 0 gives p50, p95, p99 without storing individual samples
  |
  style.fill: "#FFF3E0"
  style.stroke: "#E65100"
}
legend: {
  near: bottom-right
  label: "Color Legend"
  width: 200
  legend_text: |md
    🟢 Fast path (<8μs)
    🟡 Normal I/O (8-64μs)  
    🟠 Slow path (64μs-1ms)
    🔴 Timeout zone (>1ms)
  |
  style.fill: "#F5F5F5"
  style.stroke: "#BDBDBD"
}